<TEXT>
recent rains in the nations midsection 
have raised the waters of the ohio river enough to clear a logjam 
of barge traffic that has existed for weeks the coast guard said 
friday 
the ohio river like the mississippi and missouri had shrunk to 
alltime lows earlier this month at one point 84 barge tows were 
backed up on the ohio near this southern illinois town a few miles 
north of the the point where the ohio meets the mississippi 
but by friday evening all backedup barges had cleared the area 
and all size restrictions on the tows were lifted said coast guard 
ensign rick johnson 
upriver at louisville the ohio averaged 5 billion gallons of 
water a day during the first half of the month 84 percent below 
normal the us geological survey said 
the current flow rate wasnt available friday but during one 
24hour period this week the river rose 5 feet johnson said the 
river stage at cairo was 61 feet tuesday and 1269 feet friday he 
said 
however the coast guard continued to rout traffic one way at a 
time through an auxiliary channel near mound city while a dredge 
scooped out silt from the main route 
it still has a lot of work to do in the area johnson said 
the question of whether barge traffic continues to flow freely 
will be answered by the amount of rainfall he added 
i dont know how long it will stay this way johnson said 
if we get a dry spell like weve been having the river will go 
right back down and well be back where we were 
</TEXT>
