<TEXT>
republicans say they plan to begin a 
challenge possibly as early as today in an effort to keep lloyd 
bentsens hands off his senate campaign kitty now that he also is 
officially the democratic nominee for vice president 
although bentsens two races are legal in texas the dual 
candidacies are unprecedented since presidential campaigns became 
publicly financed in 1976 and the national republican senatorial 
committee plans to mount a challenge 
republicans contend bentsen nominated as democratic 
presidential candidate michael dukakis running mate thursday night 
in atlanta should be barred from spending his senate contributions 
because they also will benefit the democratic presidential 
campaign which is limited to spending 46 million in public funds 
were going to sit back and go to school on how these guys 
bend break and mutilate the spending limits in the presidential 
election said ben ginsberg legal counsel to the committee 
bentsen who has a reputation for being one of the most 
successful fundraisers in congress raised 61 million from jan 
1 1987 to june 30 of this year while his republican challenger 
in his senate race rep beau boulter has collected 587254 
during the period according to the federal election commission 
ginsberg said the group tentatively planned to file a petition 
with the fec today seeking to block certification of 
dukakisbentsen ticket so the team cant receive public campaign 
money the petition is the first step to challenging bentsens use 
of his senate campaign funds ginsberg said 
texas with its 29 electoral votes will be a prime battleground 
in the race for president between dukakis and the certain 
republican nominee vice president george bush who calls houston 
home 
the gop contends dukakis will have an unfair advantage in the 
lone star state and elsewhere as long as bentsen can raise and 
spend unlimited amounts on his senate campaign 
if bentsen were to drop out of the senate race before the 
november election boulter would win the seat should bentsen win 
both races and become vice president gov bill clements would 
appoint a successor pending a special election 
nearly 17 million of the 61 million bentsen raised during 
1987 and the first six months of this year was from political 
action committee contributions boulter collected 73911 in pac 
donations during the period 
bentsen spent about 3 million during the 18 monthperiod while 
boulter spent 582721 according to finance reports filed this 
week with the fec 
based on campaign finance reports for the period jan 1 1987 
to the end of march 1988 the fec ranked bentsen as the leader 
among congressional candidates in overall contributions and pac 
receipts 
for the spring reporting period april 1 through june 30 
bentsen raised and spent just over 1 million about 236169 of 
the money raised came from pac contributions 
</TEXT>
