<TEXT>
a federal appeals court has overturned a judges 
decision to combine 35000 asbestosrelated lawsuits against a 
chicago company after some of those who filed the suits objected 
last month us district judge robert l vining jr 
consolidated 35000 personal injury law suits pending against 
raymark industries inc in response to a defense motion in an 
asbestosrelated injury claim of an atlanta couple 
that decision which had created one of the largest personal 
injury cases and the largest asbestosrelated injury case ever was 
overturned by three judges of the 11th us circuit court of 
appeals 
according to federal court records more than 100 plaintiffs 
objected to having their lawsuits against raymark consolidated into 
one complaint because none of them had been notified about legal 
efforts that sought the class action the plaintiffs also 
complained that the evidence considered by the federal court was 
not enough to justify such a major decision 
in an order wednesday judge frank johnson wrote that the 
district courts order will delay resolution of their claims 
indefinitely 
the courts order which essentially moves their cases back to 
square one could hardly place petitioners in a more drastic 
predicament wrote johnson 
raymark has been the target of 70000 personal injury lawsuits 
involving 82000 people in the past 10 years the suits claim that 
people developed asbestosrelated diseases after exposure to 
insulation and other raymark products at construction and 
shipbuilding sites and factories 
half of the 70000 cases already have been resolved by trial 
outofcourt settlement or dismissal 
</TEXT>
