<TEXT>
south korean political leaders said 
today they would try to respond positively to a north korean call 
for talks on a nonaggression pact between the two bitter rivals 
leaders of the souths four main political parties said they 
would cooperate with each other to produce a united response by the 
end of next week that could clear the way for talks 
we will make efforts to seek an early realization of 
interkorea parliamentary talks said opposition leader kim 
daejung 
communist north korea sent an invitation thursday to the south 
korean national assembly for talks with the supreme peoples 
assembly in pyongyang on a nonaggression pact drawn up by the 
communist north 
south korean government and opposition leaders said preliminary 
negotiations would be needed to work out the terms and details 
before any agreement could be reached on parliamentary talks 
kim opposition leaders kim youngsam and kim jongpil and 
government democratic justice party chairman yoon giljoong said 
they would try to use the norths proposals to promote contacts to 
ease tension on the divided peninsula 
south korean defense minister oh jabok warned senior commanders 
today that the north had substantial military superiority over the 
south and its forces were poised for a lightning attack 
the north korean proposal received modest coverage in the south 
korean media many observers said the proposal did not appear to be 
a major new development 
the rival koreas have presented a series of proposals in recent 
months to ease tension and establish peace on the divided 
peninsula but each side has tended to ignore the others 
proposals insisting its plans be followed 
talks between parliamentary delegations on a nonaggression pact 
collapsed in 1986 when north korea pulled out to protest routine 
ussouth korean military exercises similar efforts in the early 
1970s also failed to make any progress 
a government spokesman speaking on condition of anonymity said 
talks between the rival governments should be held at the same time 
as the parliamentary talks he said any decision on a pact by the 
south would be taken by the seoul administration 
south korean insistence on intergovernment talks could block 
the parliamentary talks since north korea has been refusing to 
deal with the seoul government both governments claim they are the 
sole legitimate government of korea 
north korea refused to accept letters earlier this month from 
the seoul government calling for political economic and 
humanitarian talks on easing relations south korean president roh 
taewoo called for a major peace effort but the north refused to 
accept the letter outlining the proposal 
north korea has been insisting for months it wants to deal 
directly with the people in the south and has continued to 
denounce the seoul government as a usbacked puppet regime it 
apparently sent a letter to the national assembly for this reason 
the south korean government and the oppositiondominated 
national assembly agree any talks with the north must be under the 
administrations direction any north korean delegation at peace 
talks would be under direct government control because the norths 
assembly is a powerless rubberstamp body 
south korean political parties all support peaceful 
reunification but also fear the north remains determined to extend 
communist rule over the peninsula 
political leaders in seoul expressed concern north korea did not 
respond to the national assemblys call to take part in the 1988 
olympic games in seoul the north korean proposal was in response 
to the assemblys call for pyongyang not to boycott the games 
north korea has been demanding to cohost the olympics but 
international olympic officials said the games can only be awarded 
to a single city 
the korean peninsula was divided by us and soviet forces that 
ended the japanese occupation at the end of world war ii efforts 
to reunite the peninsula failed and separate governments were 
declared in 1948 
the communist north invaded the south in 1950 to start the 
korean war about 42000 us troops are based in the south under a 
mutual defense treaty 
</TEXT>
