<TEXT>
intravenous drug abusers have replaced 
homosexuals as the chief risk group for contracting hepatitis b 
federal health officials said suggesting national efforts to 
vaccinate them have failed 
the centers for disease control reported thursday that its 
ongoing study of hepatitis has found a striking increase in 
hepatitis b among iv drug abusers and a decrease among homosexuals 
that was likely produced by fear of aids 
miriam alter the cdcs chief of hepatitis surveillance said 
she could not explain the increase among drug abusers no reason 
has been found other than the fact that apparently theyre not 
changing their behavior she said 
hepatitis an inflammation of the liver caused by one of several 
viruses is contagious and can be fatal hepatitis b tends to be 
more severe than hepatitis a and is a more serious problem for 
health officials because hepatitis b patients can become lifetime 
carriers of the infection 
since 1985 drug abuse has surpassed homosexual activity as the 
chief risk factor for hepatitis b infection the cdc said in its 
weekly report 
the drop in homosexual cases is most likely a result of 
modification of highrisk sexual behavior prompted by the fear of 
aids the atlantabased health agency said 
even though a vaccine has been available for six years the cdc 
said there has been a steady increase in hepatitis b cases 
nationwide over the last decade the united states has about 
300000 infections per year now compared with 200000 per year in 
the late 1970s alter said adding that exact figures are 
unavailable because only a small percentage of cases are reported 
she suggested that efforts to vaccinate highrisk groups against 
hepatitis b have failed because of the difficulty in identifying 
highrisk people and because the vaccine must be administered in 
three doses over six months 
its hard to find them and to get them to come back for all 
three doses she said 
the cdc report cited another possible reasons for the failure of 
vaccination efforts many patients are already infected by the time 
they are identified as belonging to a risk group 
failure to overcome these obstacles will necessitate 
consideration of a broader immunization strategy the cdc said 
such a strategy could include routine hepatitis immunizations 
for children or adolescents alter said although the cdc is not 
yet recommending any particular strategy 
we want to make people aware that the current strategy is not 
working and to make people think about possible alternative 
strategies that may become necessary she said 
the cdcs hepatitis study begun in 1982 monitors four counties 
denver county colo jefferson county ala pierce county 
wash and pinellas county fla to determine trends in hepatitis 
infection 
the cdc said drug abusers accounted for 28 percent of the 
hepatitis b cases in the four counties in 1987 up from 15 percent 
in 1982 by contrast the percentage of homosexual cases dropped 
from 20 percent in 1982 to 9 percent in 1987 
hepatitis can be transmitted through sexual contact sharing of 
iv needles frequent contact with blood in the health professions 
household contact with a carrier blood transfusions dialysis and 
residency in an institution for the developmentally disabled 
more than 30 percent of the cases have no known source the cdc 
said 
</TEXT>
