<DOCNO> AP880722-0079 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
alzheimers disease may be caused in 
some cases by an infectious agent according to preliminary 
findings by yale university researchers 
there is no known cause or cure for the disease 
the researchers said it could take three to four more years to 
confirm their initial observations but they released the findings 
to stimulate more research dr laura manuelidis a member of the 
research team said thursday 
we could be wrong but then in the past we have been right 
she said 
the study was reported in the july issue of the proceedings of 
the national academy of sciences 
alzheimers is a progressive irreversible neurological disorder 
that mostly strikes people over 65 and has an estimated 25 million 
american victims its symptoms include memory loss impairment of 
judgment personality change and loss of language skills 
the researchers said their findings suggest that some people may 
become infected with alzheimers through infectious virallike 
agents similar to those that cause creutzfeldtjakob disease a 
less common form of dementia 
the scientists based their hypothesis on a study of blood from 
11 volunteers who had at least two relatives siblings or parents 
with alzheimers 
the reseachers found that the white blood cells from five of the 
volunteers one of whom has since developed clear signs of 
alzheimers produced brain lesions in hamsters similar to those 
they had seen in rodents infected with creutzfeldtjakob disease 
these transmission results raise the intriguing possibility 
that cjdlike agents may be involved in at least some forms of 
alzheimers disease the report said 
previous attempts to transmit alzheimers to animals were 
unsuccessful 
dr andrew monjan deputy associate director for neuroscience 
and neuropsychology at the national institute on aging in bethesda 
md said it was premature to make any sort of statement that 
there is an infectious etiology to alzheimers 
but he said if you are going to find an infectious agent 
youve got to look at an earlier stage of the disease i would hope 
that the paper would stimulate other investigators to pursue 
similar lines 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

