<TEXT>
censors are debating whether to ban sex and 
serious crimes from chinese movies and are considering establishing 
the countrys first rating system to keep children from seeing some 
films altogether 
the rating system would protect younger children from movies 
that could harm their healthy minds the official china daily 
and outlook magazine reported 
a proposed law now would mark the first time since communist 
china was established in 1949 that explicit standards have been set 
about what can and cannot be portrayed in a chinese movie 
in the past censorship changed with the political climate of 
the country when the country was ruled by hardline leftists 
censorship was quite strict when moderates took command 
censorship was relatively lax 
outlook quoted chen haosu vice minister of radio film and 
television as saying the regulations were needed to eliminate the 
ambiguity surrounding artistic expression 
if theres no law then you can interfere with anything 
haosu was quoted as saying 
but some artists in china say they thrive on the ambiguity 
preferring to work within the present vague situation where a 
liberal turn in the political wind might allow a controversial work 
to slip by 
china produces more than 100 feature films a year and boasts the 
largest movie industry in the world employing 500000 workers 
in the 10 years since china began to open to the west about a 
dozen movies have been killed by chinas censors ai zhisheng 
the minister of radio film and television told outlook 
others have been revised with the help of the film company 
he said 
outlook said censors agreed chinese films should not hurt china 
or the unity of its numerous nationalities nor should they distort 
history or exert an unhealthy influence on the morals of the people 
but it said censors disagreed on nudity and crime 
an article of the proposed law bans naked bodies and sex scenes 
from all movies but outlook said some officials argued nudity and 
sex should be forbidden only when they have no relation to the plot 
another proposed article forbids graphic descriptions of 
criminal acts because officials fear they might trigger copycat 
crimes outlook said some officials favored limiting the clause to 
only serious crimes such as rape and drug trafficking 
outlook said some officials were also pushing to institute a 
rating system for movies 
there are many movies that arent good for children or that 
shouldnt be seen without the presence of an older family member 
chen was quoted as saying he said china needed to establish a 
rating system as soon as possible 
