<TEXT>
author john hersey apologized friday for using 
uncredited material from another writers book in a new yorker 
article on james agee 
hersey said he should have credited some of his sources 
especially laurence bergreens james agee a life the most 
comprehensive and thoroughly researched biography of agee so far 
published 
bergreen had told his lawyer to complain to the new yorker and 
to houghton mifflin which had commissioned the piece as an 
introduction to a new edition of agees let us now praise famous 
men 
houghton mifflin said in a statement mr hersey feels that 
several of the sources on which he draws for facts about mr agees 
life beyond his own recollections should be credited and they 
will be 
agee a critic novelist journalist and screenwriter died in 
1955 
the facts that a biographer or historian digs up dont belong 
to him they belong to the public anybody has a right to use 
them hersey said friday in a telephone interview from his home 
on marthas vineyard 
but the one thing that is protected is the mode of 
expression he continued if in the course of a 12000word 
article i used a dozen or so words i certainly did not 
intend to steal them from him 
he said he thought there was a fine line between ones right 
to use material and ones respect for the work of another writer 
and that his offense was not great in terms of normal practice 
bergreen said he came across the july 18 issue of the new yorker 
during a lunch break and because i had interviewed hersey for my 
biography i turned to read it with considerable interest 
as i read it i discovered that there were a number of passages 
which were very closely modeled on my own in the book there were 
numerous instances where he was using my phrasing my choice of 
words and structure and so on 
with the exception of an introductory anecdote about agee the 
rest of the piece which was a rather long one amounted to a 
condensation of my biography bergreen said 
