homosexual women experience much more stress than heterosexuals but 
share similar concerns about physical and mental health its 
authors said friday 
it dispels some of the myths about lesbianism said 
coauthor caitlin ryan social worker and researcher 
the national lesbian health care survey undertaken with some 
federal funding was presented at the weeklong 10th national 
lesbian and gay health conference and aids forum which ends 
tuesday 
the survey by ryan and coauthor judith bradford of virginia 
commonwealth university was conducted by sending 10page 
questionnaires to 4600 women the 2000 respondents from 
throughout the nation ranged from 17 to 80 years old 
eighty percent of the respondents were between 2544 and about 
70 percent were in professional or managerial jobs 46 percent of 
participants had one child or more or were childless but wanted to 
have one most lived in metropolitan areas 
ryan said she had no error margin for the results because the 
study was the first of its kind and because no one knows the size 
of the base population of lesbians 
the data indicate that lesbians are very much like 
heterosexual women in their concerns about health care and mental 
health concerns bradford told an audience of about 200 people 
who attended the survey presentation 
but it is quite different as far as access to nondiscriminate 
care and the level of stress she said 
among the studys findings 
substance abuse among lesbians becomes greater as they age 
especially among the 5055 age group the older lesbians tend to 
be very isolated ryan said their partner may die and they 
become very depressed and turn to substance abuse 
more than onethird of those surveyed said they were physically 
abused as a child 
