<TEXT>
a medical physicists error allowed 153 
cancer patients to receive radiation overdoses at the royal devon 
and exeter hospital in southwest england health officials said 
friday 
of those patients who received the 25 percent extra dosages 
while undergoing radation therapy between february and july of this 
year 22 have died according to exeter health official david king 
king said however that the deaths could not be attributed 
directly to the increased radiation another doctor said it was 
unlikely but possible that the overdoses led to deaths 
king said it was a mathematical miscalculation and the 
medical physicist is mortified he said the error discovered 
eight days ago has been corrected the physicists name was not 
released 
the exeter health and safety executive has begun an inquiry into 
the mistake and another investigation will be conducted by charles 
joslin a professor at leeds university radiotherapy department 
king said 
exeter radiotherapist dr chris rowlands said in the majority 
of cases most people i think will be unaffected by this 
particular error but the patients tolerance to radiation varies 
asked by a reporter if the error could have led to deaths 
rowlands said i think it is most unlikely but in a limited 
number of cases in certain sites that has to be a possibility 
he said there was no such thing as a normal dosage because 
amounts of treatment varied greatly 
hylton meire a consultant radiologist at kings college 
hospital london said the 25 percent overdose given to treat a 
tumor was within the normal range of error 
when dealing with therapeutic doses of radiation the 
calculation is to minimize the damage to surrounding tissue while 
giving tumors a fatal dose he said and calculations could vary 
from one hospital to another by as much as 50 percent 
</TEXT>
