dorcas hardy head of the us social security 
administration said friday his organization will train chinese 
managers for chinas fledging efforts to set up retirement programs 
for its aging work force 
ms hardy who arrived in beijing monday at the invitation of 
the ministry of labor said 50 chinese will be invited to the 
united states next year to study how the 53yearold american 
social security system works 
we are in a position to provide a helping hand in chinas 
progress in setting up programs for retirees she said 
she said that since her arrival she had met officials from the 
civil affairs and labor ministries and the china fund for the 
handicapped 
communist china has never developed a national pension program 
staterun factories are responsible for paying retirees up to 75 
percent of their basic salaries causing heavy financial burdens as 
the number of retired workers increases and economic reforms put 
more pressure on enterprises to turn in a profit 
farmers accounting for more than threefourths of chinas 
population of 1 billion and the growing number of private 
entrepreneurs often have no guaranteed source of income after 
retirement 
china is also facing a rapid aging of its population the 
percentage of those aged more than 60 will increase from 84 
percent at present to 20 percent in the year 2025 
ms hardy said it was an undertaking of monumental proportions 
when the most populous nation on earth begins to construct its own 
social security program 
ms hardy said she advised china to maintain its strong emphasis 
on the family system and to reconsider its mandatory retirement 
age men in staterun enterprises now must retire at age 60 most 
women must leave work at age 55 
she said she also discussed us approaches to burdensharing 
among the government the company and the employee china recently 
began experimenting with programs where the employee contributes a 
small amount from his paycheck every month for retirement benefits 
most workers in china still pay no direct social security tax 
ms hardy said most retirement payments in china are made 
directly by the factory to its former employee she saw little 
evidence of computerization of records or the use of actuaries to 
project future demographic trends china must get a better 
system she said 
