<TEXT>
monsters can be made out of the most ordinary of 
men according to playwright jon robin baitz 
it depends on how they adapt or accommodate themselves to the 
world around them and when the world is as stratified rigid 
unfeeling and corrupt as the white south africa portrayed in the 
film society they can develop into some pretty hardhearted 
creatures 
the film society which opened thursday at offbroadways 
second stage examines one such sad and frightening tranformation 
the play is a promising new york stage debut for the 26yearold 
author an american who lived in south africa for six years 
baitz has come up with a provocative look at the depressing 
metamorphosis of jonathon balton a nebbish of a man who became a 
schoolteacher because its such a quiet occupation and because 
he couldnt get a job as a radio actor 
jonathon teaches at blenheim an uppercrust boys school that 
has fallen on hard times the prep school serves as a microcosm for 
white south african society 
there are the members of the old guard ruled by the headmaster 
a pragmatic man who is more concerned about the survival of the 
school than the students he is assisted by a fiery rightwing 
instructor who is dying of spinal cancer and who rails against 
communism enveloping the country they form the bulwark against the 
younger teachers who presumably would be more enlightened about the 
school and south african society 
jonathon will have none of it instead of teaching he would 
rather preside over the schools film society where he can screen 
old doris day movies and block out his job and the real world 
the time is the early 1970s the years when baitz also lived in 
south africa the teachers and the students are aware of the racial 
tumult outside the school but none of the strife is present at 
blenheim a colonial institution that has outlived its usefulness 
at first it seems as if terry a temperamental firebrand of a 
teacher will be the plays central character its terry who sets 
the play in motion bringing in a black activist priest to speak at 
the schools centenary celebration the clergyman is arrested and 
later dies in jail supposedly of a heart attack no one except 
terry and his wife nan who also teaches at blenheim seems very 
concerned 
jonathons importance to the play is revealed gradually his 
mother a member of the old aristocracy uses her influence and 
money to get him a better job at the school at first he is 
willing to bring his friends along on his good fortune but 
practicality and ambition take over 
baitz is a strong forceful writer hes terrific at conjuring 
up pictures of south african life there are two such set pieces 
one a long description by nan of a particularly recalcitrant 
servant who worked for her parents and the other a poignant 
remembrance by jonathon of his botched attempt to kill a cow in the 
presence of his fathers african workers 
the play begins slowly and director john tillinger doesnt rush 
the actors or the action each character is allowed to reveal 
motivations gradually 
nathan lane who plays jonathon has always excelled in comic 
roles parts that demand a maximum of mugging he has risen to a 
different challenge here capturing the mans ordinary qualities 
particularly when he tries to articulate his forlorn and pathetic 
dreams about a show business career 
william glover and dillon evans are the very models of outdated 
and unfeeling british propriety while there is icy perfection from 
margaret hilton as jonathons practical mother daniel gerroll 
exudes the righteous anger of baitzs onenote radical teacher 
while laila robins brings an honesty to nan the plays one 
sympathetic character 
the film society is an impressive intelligent effort by 
baitz a playwright whose next work will be watched even more 
closely 
</TEXT>
