<DOCNO> AP880722-0293 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
mcgrawhill inc has a good chance of tracking 
down the culprit if someone leaked advance information on stocks 
spotlighted in its widely read business week magazine experts said 
friday 
the publisher said thursday that its legal counsel is 
investigating suspicious price movements and heavy trading in 
stocks mentioned in the inside wall street column before 
business week was available to the public 
while the investigation encompasses mcgrawhills entire 
operation from its inhouse staff to the four plants where 
business week is printed the experts expressed doubt the 
magazines editorial staff was involved 
most agreed the conviction of a wall street journal reporter who 
leaked advance information to a stockbroker would deter journalists 
from making a similar error in judgment 
in 1985 reporter r foster winans was convicted of passing tips 
about items scheduled to appear in the financial newspapers 
influential heard on the street column he was sentenced to 18 
months in prison 
you would think the winans case would scare editorial 
people said ralph ferrara former general counsel of the 
securities and exchange commission and a partner of the new york 
law firm of debevoise amp plimpton 
the winans case was far simpler to investigate because that 
column was written by only two reporters handled by a few editors 
and printed immediately the experts said they said extensive 
legwork would be required to follow business weeks publication 
trail 
the magazines 960000 weekly issues are printed early thursday 
morning released to the press after the market closes that day and 
to the general public on friday 
in order to trace the leak mcgrawhill is likely to team up 
with the enforcement operations of stock exchanges and ultimately 
the sec 
that way mcgrawhill can get the names of the purchasers and 
sellers of the stocks and match them with the files of their 
employees ferrara said 
if the leak occurred at one of the plants which are located in 
connecticut california wisconsin and pennsylvania and do contract 
work for mcgrawhill it would be more difficult to track but still 
possible the experts said 
james ratcliffe director of public affairs at rr donnelley amp 
sons inc which prints business week in connecticut and 
california said the company had launched its own investigation 
separate from mcgrawhills inquiry 
he said that while only about 150 employees work the night shift 
when business week is printed in connecticut almost anybody at 
the plant could lay their hands on it the plant employs 550 
people 
sam scott miller a partner in the new york firm orrick 
herrington amp sutcliffe and a member of the securities industry 
associations trading practices committee said its certainly 
easier to connect up with a printer whos doing it in his own name 
and its not too much more difficult to find someone whos 
brotherinlaw or cousin is trading on the information 
it is difficult to finger someone with no business or social 
connection to the information but its definitely still 
possible scott said 
these people dont just pop up out of the blue he said 
adding that the first thing investigators do is make geographical 
connections among the trades 
once a pattern is nailed down authorities begin questioning 
individuals 
the sec and the stock exchanges have proven to be 
extraordinarily resourceful in networking these deals ferrara 
said with a little information from personnel files youll be 
surprised how bells and whistles start to engage 
there have been a number of cases involving printers who traded 
on information taken from financial documents lawyers said but 
one problem is that a case is nearly impossible to build unless the 
employer has a policy specifically restricting such activity 
donnelleys ratcliffe said all employees are made aware that 
they are handling highly confidential information and any misuse 
will result in disciplinary action to date he said there have been 
no firings for that reason 
a spokesman for wa kreuger co which prints business week at 
a plant in wisconsin was said to be out of his office and 
unreachable for comment 
</TEXT>
