most crop futures prices moved lower friday on the chicago board 
of trade in a lackluster session featuring profittaking and 
uncertainty about the farm belt weather outlook for the weekend and 
beyond 
on other markets silver futures were sharply higher livestock 
and meat were mostly higher energy futures were lower and 
stockindex futures retreated 
soybean prices for nearterm delivery fell for the fifth 
straight day bringing the august contract to just over 830 a 
bushel the lowest price for nearmonth delivery since june 2 
grain and soybean prices fell sharply earlier in the week as 
showers swept across the dusty midwest the market has been unable 
to sustain a rally since then because of speculation that the 
drought pattern that drove soybeans to a 15year high of nearly 11 
a bushel on june 23 has weakened analysts said 
the bulls are really grasping here trying to get things 
recovered said victor lespinasse a trader with dean witter 
reynolds inc in chicago what we need to make prices rise is a 
return to hot dry weather 
forecasters generally expected temperatures in the midwest to 
turn warmer over the weekend but some also predicted scattered 
showers and traders were hesitant to establish new positions 
everybodys a little gunshy because the last time we were 
supposed to just get showers we got some good rains said john 
frazier grain specialist with balfour maclaine corp in chicago 
after the close the national weather service issued a 
6to10day forecast calling for hot and mostly dry conditions to 
prevail in the farm belt during the latter part of next week 
losses in the wheat market were limited by agriculture 
department reports of new export deals with china india and iraq 
analysts said 
wheat settled 2 cents lower to 1 cent higher with the contract 
for delivery in september at 384 a bushel corn was cent to 4 
cents lower with september at 312 a bushel oats were 9 cents 
lower to 2 cents higher with september at 260 a bushel soybeans 
were 12 cents lower to 20 cents higher with august at 830 a 
bushel 
