the market reacted with skepticism to potentially bullish 
reports that the peruvian central bank planned to acquire all of 
the nations silver output accounting for 2035 percent of world 
production instead of allowing it to be sold on the international 
market 
if in fact they do hold it back for a long period of time 
its very bullish for silver said jack barbanel director of 
futures trading for gruntal amp co in new york 
but he said the information is really mixed on whether 
theyre going to hold it back and the market just cannot gauge 
what is going to be the final outcome of this 
gold settled unchanged to 20 cents higher with august at 44290 
a troy ounce silver was 131 cents to 148 cents lower with july 
at 7606 a troy ounce 
nearmonth pork futures advanced their permitted limits on the 
chicago mercantile exchange for the second consecutive session in 
response to strong cash markets and anticipation of a seasonal 
upswing in retail demand 
cattle futures advanced in cautious trading ahead of the usdas 
quarterly 13state and monthly 7state cattleonfeed reports 
the reports showed slightly more cattle being fattened for 
slaughter than the trade had expected and analysts pronounced it 
slightly bearish for nearterm contracts 
more startling was the usdas projected thirdquarter marketings 
figure of 62 million head which would make the number of cattle 
sold for slaughter during the current quarter the largest in us 
history said chuck levitt livestock analyst in chicago for 
shearson lehman hutton inc 
the usda also issued a monthly cold storage report showing 1047 
million pounds of frozen pork bellies in storage on june 30 a 220 
percent increase over a year ago and the thirdlargest june 30 
figure in history 
